  "prompt": "How does the Aereo antenna work?",
  "response": "Aereo was a service that used tiny individual antennas to capture over-the-air broadcast television signals for each subscriber. Here's how it worked:\n\n1. Antenna Array\n- Each subscriber was assigned a dedicated, dime-sized antenna\n- These antennas were housed in large data centers\n- Antennas could be individually tuned to receive local broadcast signals\n\n2. Signal Capture\n- When a subscriber selected a channel, their specific antenna would tune to and capture that broadcast signal\n- The signal was then converted to a digital format\n\n3. Cloud Storage and Streaming\n- The captured signal was stored briefly in a cloud-based server\n- The digital signal was then streamed to the subscriber's device (computer, smartphone, tablet)\n\n4. Individual Transmission\n- Aereo emphasized that each antenna was unique to a subscriber\n- This was part of their legal argument that they were not a public broadcast service\n\n5. Legal Challenges\n- Aereo was sued by broadcast networks for copyright infringement\n- In 2014, the Supreme Court ruled against Aereo, effectively shutting down the service\n- The Court determined that Aereo's service was essentially a cable system, which requires licensing fees\n\nThe innovative antenna approach was ultimately deemed illegal, and Aereo ceased operations.",
